    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Tuberous perennial with 2-6 elongate-oval, pointed leaves; the lower leaves spreading and the higher ones tightly sheathed around an upright fleshy stem. This bears a spike of spaced greenish flowers, sometimes with a purple tinge. Flowers have a sac-like lip with a narrow entrance and slender spurs and have a pungent clove-like smell, especially at night.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10175",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Stems up to about 55 cm long, flower spurs about 18 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10176",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Along a broad coastal band from about Lambert’s Bay to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10177",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common on sandy and humus-rock soils in a wide coastal swathe across Western Cape, often where partly-shaded or in shelter of rocks and bushes. &nbsp;Eaten by rock-hyraxes.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10178",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10179",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers August to October.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10180",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>One of many regional species in this genus, but distinguished from most others by the greenish flowers. Other species with similar habitats include the Shy satyre <i>S. humile</i> which has cream flowers and the Pink satyre <i>S. corneum,</i> which has a conspicuous head of many rosy-pink flowers.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10181",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Manning, J (2007). Field Guide to Fynbos. Cape Town: Random House Struik. (p. 156).<br><br>Manning, J & Goldblatt, P (2000). South African Wild Flower Guide 7: West Coast. Botanical Society of South Africa (p. 80).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_10182",
            "longText": null,
